cultural intermediaries, transmitting wisdom and values from the past; at the same time, they were deeply involved in some of the most contentious and far-reaching changes in lay piety, and in economic and social structures. The author challenges the predominantly didactic approach to the verse, in an attempt to historicize the category of the intellectual, as someone caught in the duality of the worlds of contingency and absolute values. The book will have a broad appeal to medievalists, in part because of the topics covered (feudalism, gender, nationhood, and religion), in part because many poems are either adaptations from French and Latin or have counterparts in other literatures (e.g., the romances or Alexander and Apollonius, the miracles of the Virgin Mary). JULIAN WEISS is Professor of Medieval and Early Modern Spanish at King's College London.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aRomances, SpanishxHistory and criticism. 0aSpanish poetryxHistory and criticismyTo 1500. 0aSpanish poetryyTo 1500xHistory and criticism. 4aHispanic Studies. 4aMedieval Literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / Spanish & Portuguese.2bisacsh  aMester de Clerecía.  aintellectual history.  anarrative poems.  athirteenth-century Spain.1 aWeiss, Julian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013z978311143139040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978184615493540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781846154935423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781846154935/original  a978-3-11-143139-0  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013b2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles